# Assuming your DataFrame is named 'data' and 'trans_date_trans_time' is already converted to datetime

# Extract the hour from the datetime column
data['hour'] = data['trans_date_trans_time'].dt.hour

# Define time of day categories
def categorize_time(hour):
    if 6 <= hour < 12:
        return 'Morning'
    elif 12 <= hour < 17:
        return 'Afternoon'
    elif 17 <= hour < 22:
        return 'Evening'
    else:
        return 'Night'

# Apply the categorization function
data['time_of_day'] = data['hour'].apply(categorize_time)

# Count fraudulent transactions for each time of day
fraud_by_time = data[data['is_fraud'] == 1]['time_of_day'].value_counts()

# Count total transactions for each time of day
total_by_time = data['time_of_day'].value_counts()

# Calculate the proportion of fraudulent transactions per time of day
fraud_proportion_time = fraud_by_time / total_by_time

# Plot the proportion of fraudulent transactions by time of day
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.barplot(x=fraud_proportion_time.index, y=fraud_proportion_time.values, order=['Morning', 'Afternoon', 'Evening', 'Night'])
plt.title('Proportion of Fraudulent Transactions by Time of Day')
plt.xlabel('Time of Day')
plt.ylabel('Proportion of Fraudulent Transactions')
plt.show()

The counts show variations in the number of fraudulent transactions across the week. Observations: Saturday (5) and Sunday (6) have the highest number of fraudulent transactions.

Implications: This suggests that fraudsters may be more active on weekends. It's worth investigating why this might be the case. It could be due to: Increased transaction volume on weekends. Less stringent security measures on weekends. Fraudsters taking advantage of reduced staffing or monitoring. "Most frauds occurred at night"

This is a very important piece of information. Combining this with the day of week information, it means that the highest amount of fraud is happening on the weekends, during the night time.

Customer Behavior: This column can be used to analyze customer spending patterns. You can group transactions by credit card number to see how often each card is used, the average transaction amount, etc.

Fraud Detection: Analyzing transaction patterns for individual credit cards can be extremely useful. For example, sudden changes in spending habits, unusual transaction locations, or rapid sequences of transactions might indicate fraud.

In [26]:
# Assuming your DataFrame is named 'data'

# Number of transactions per credit card
transactions_per_card = data['cc_num'].value_counts().reset_index()
transactions_per_card.columns = ['cc_num', 'num_transactions']
data = pd.merge(data, transactions_per_card, on='cc_num', how='left')

# Average transaction amount per credit card
avg_amount_per_card = data.groupby('cc_num')['amt'].mean().reset_index()
avg_amount_per_card.columns = ['cc_num', 'avg_transaction_amount']
data = pd.merge(data, avg_amount_per_card, on='cc_num', how='left')

# Example of time between transactions.
# This requires the data to be sorted by time, and then grouped by cc_num.
# Then the diff function can be used.

print(data[['cc_num', 'num_transactions', 'avg_transaction_amount']].head())

Implications:

The weak positive correlation with avg_transaction_amount suggests that this feature might have some predictive power for fraud detection. High average transaction amounts could be a red flag. The very weak negative correlation of num_transactions means that this feature by itself is not a strong predictor of fraud.

from scipy import stats

# T-test for average transaction amount
t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(peak1_data['amt'], peak2_data['amt'])
print(f"T-test for average transaction amount: t={t_stat:.4f}, p={p_value:.4f}")

T-test for average transaction amount: t=6.7801, p=0.0000

The T-test results you provided are highly significant:

Interpretation of T-Test Results:

T-statistic (t = 6.7801): The t-statistic measures the difference between the means of the two groups relative to the variation within the groups.   A large absolute value of the t-statistic indicates a substantial difference between the means.

P-value (p = 0.0000): A p-value of 0.0000 (or very close to zero) means that the probability of observing the data if there were no actual difference between the average transaction amounts of the two merchant peaks is extremely low. In practical terms, this means that the difference in average transaction amounts is highly statistically significant.

Implications:

The T-test results provide strong evidence that the average transaction amounts for merchants in Peak 1 and Peak 2 are significantly different. This confirms that the observed difference is not due to random chance.

While statistical significance is important, it's also essential to consider the practical significance of the difference.   In this case, the average transaction amount difference was not huge, but it still was statistically different.

The average transaction amount is a relevant feature for distinguishing between merchants in the two peaks.

# Chi-square test for category distribution
peak1_category_counts = peak1_data['category'].value_counts()

# Create a contingency table
contingency_table = pd.DataFrame([peak1_category_counts, peak2_category_counts]).fillna(0)

chi2_stat, p_value, _, _ = stats.chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
print(f"Chi-square test for category distribution: chi2={chi2_stat:.4f}, p={p_value:.4f}")

Chi-square test for category distribution: chi2=806207.0000, p=0.0000

Interpretation of Chi-Square Test Results:

Chi-square Statistic (chi2 = 806207.0000): A very large Chi-square statistic indicates a substantial difference between the observed and expected frequencies in the contingency table. In this context, it signifies that the category distributions between the two merchant peaks are very different.

P-value (p = 0.0000): A p-value of 0.0000 (or essentially zero) means that the probability of observing the data if the category distributions were the same is incredibly low. This provides overwhelming evidence to reject the null hypothesis.

Implications:

The Chi-square test results confirm that the category distributions for merchants in Peak 1 and Peak 2 are significantly different. This means that the differences we observed in the category proportions are not due to random chance.

The highly significant difference in category distributions further reinforces the idea that the two peaks represent distinct merchant segments. Merchants in different peaks tend to operate in different categories.

# Calculate transaction counts per merchant
merchant_counts = data['merchant'].value_counts()

# Define outlier thresholds (e.g., 95th percentile for high outliers)
high_threshold = merchant_counts.quantile(0.95)

# Identify high outliers
high_outliers = merchant_counts[merchant_counts > high_threshold]

# Print high outliers
print("High Outlier Merchants:")
print(high_outliers)

# Define outlier thresholds (e.g., 5th percentile for low outliers)
low_threshold = merchant_counts.quantile(0.05)

# Identify low outliers
low_outliers = merchant_counts[merchant_counts < low_threshold]

# Print low outliers
print("\nLow Outlier Merchants:")
print(low_outliers)

# Example of grouping outliers into a separate category
def categorize_merchant_outlier(merchant):
    count = merchant_counts[merchant]
    if merchant in high_outliers:
        return 'High Volume Outlier'
    elif merchant in low_outliers:
        return 'Low Volume Outlier'
    else:
        return 'Normal'

# Create the 'merchant_outlier' feature

Raw counts alone don't consider the overall volume of transactions within each category. A category with a high count might simply have a high volume of transactions in general.

The percentages provide a more accurate picture of fraud risk. Even if a category has a moderate number of fraudulent transactions, its risk is higher if it also has a low volume of total transactions.

The percentage data is more valuable for assessing fraud risk. It allows you to prioritize categories with higher relative fraud rates.

For example, even though "category_gas_transport" has a higher raw fraud count than "category_food_dining", the percentage of fraud in "category_food_dining" is lower.

Extreme Skewness: The histogram shows an extremely skewed distribution. The vast majority of the data points are concentrated at the very low end of the transaction amount range (close to zero). This is evident from the extremely tall bar on the far left of the graph.

Long Tail: The distribution has a very long tail extending towards higher transaction amounts. This means that while most transactions are small, there are a few transactions with very large amounts.

Outliers: The long tail suggests the presence of outliers—transactions with unusually high amounts. These outliers are so far from the main cluster of data that they compress the visualization of the bulk of the data.

Data Characteristics: This type of distribution is common in financial data, where most transactions are small, but occasional large transactions occur (e.g., large purchases, transfers, etc.).

A balanced dataset would have a ratio closer to 1, indicating that the classes are represented in roughly equal proportions. In this case, the significant difference between the number of instances in the target class (0.57%) and the other class(es) (99.43%) indicates a strong imbalance.

Leaning towards SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) as a starting point. Here's why:

High Imbalance: The dataset has a significant class imbalance, making oversampling a strong candidate.

Dataset Size: You have a large dataset, so oversampling is computationally feasible.

SMOTE's Effectiveness: SMOTE is a popular and generally effective technique for addressing class imbalance. It generates synthetic samples of the minority class, which can help improve the model's ability to detect fraudulent transactions.

Avoiding Information Loss: Oversampling with SMOTE helps to avoid the significant information loss that can occur with undersampling.

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, roc_auc_score
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

# Separate features (X) and target (y)
X = data.drop('is_fraud', axis=1)  # Drop the target variable
y = data['is_fraud']

# Select only numeric columns for SMOTE (SMOTE cannot handle categorical)
numeric_X = X.select_dtypes(include=['number'])

# Split data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(numeric_X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42)

# Apply SMOTE to the training data
smote = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled = smote.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

# Train a Random Forest Classifier
model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)
model.fit(X_train_resampled, y_train_resampled)

# Make predictions on the test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
y_pred_proba = model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]  # Probabilities for AUC-ROC

# Evaluate the model
precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
auc_roc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_proba)

# Print the evaluation metrics
print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
print(f"F1-score: {f1:.4f}")
print(f"AUC-ROC: {auc_roc:.4f}")

Precision: 0.6763

Precision: 0.6763

This means that 67.63% of the transactions predicted as fraudulent by your model were actually fraudulent. In other words, out of all the transactions your model flagged as fraud, 67.63% were correct.

Recall: 0.8184

This means that your model correctly identified 81.84% of all actual fraudulent transactions in the dataset. In other words, it didn't miss many actual fraud cases.

F1-score: 0.7406

The F1-score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall. It provides a balanced measure of the model's accuracy. An F1-score of 0.7406 indicates a good balance between precision and recall.

AUC-ROC: 0.9867

The AUC-ROC (Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic curve) measures the model's ability to distinguish between fraudulent and non-fraudulent transactions. An AUC-ROC of 0.9867 is very high, indicating that your model has excellent discriminatory power.
